@node INTRO "DIL À Introduction"

Introduction
============

  DIL stands for "Device Intervention Layer".

  As the name says, it's used to intervene into a data-stream. It acts like a
  layer between the source application and the target device.

  Plugins are used to manipulate, encrypt or monitor the data.


  @{" Features     " link FEATURES}

  @{" Requirements " link REQUIREMENTS}
  @{" Installation " link INSTALL}

@endnode

@node FEATURES "DIL À Features"

Features
========

  Device
  ------
  - Plugin based
    - Plugins can act in two modes
      - Intervene
        - Ciphers, others that manipulate the data
      - Non-intervene
        - Monitors, analytical plugins
    - Plugin can request a seed
      - Two seed input modes
        - Keyborad (a MUI passphrase-request will open, all builtin)
        - File
  - Supported command-sets
    - EXEC, TD, ETD, TD64, SCSI, DIL
  - Command standard convertion
  - API for shell-commands
  - Advanced log-system

  Shell-commands
  --------------
  Some shell-commands helps to make things easy:

  - dilCheckCfg      Check a configuration
  - dilPlugInfo      Show informations about a plugin
  - dilGenDosDriver  Generate a DosDriver
  - dilMount         Mount a unit
  - dilUnMount       Unmount a unit
  - dilRevoke        Revoke a unit

  Plugins
  -------
  - Easy to design
  - 4 plugins so far: (alph order)
    - aes.dilp      En/decrypt the data using the AES.
    - blockmon.dilp Used to monitor the disk-access of the loaded filesystem.
    - default.dilp  Used as default, it does nothing, just forwards the data.
    - poly.dilp     En/decrypt the data using a polymorphic function.
                    The strength depends on the used blocksize and can be from
                    4096 to 262144 bits.


  @{" Introduction " link INTRO}

  @{" Requirements " link REQUIREMENTS}
  @{" Installation " link INSTALL}

@endnode

@node REQUIREMENTS "DIL À Requirements"

Software
========

  - MorphOS v1.x


  @{" Installation " link INSTALL}

@endnode

@node INSTALL "DIL À Installation"

Installation
============

  DIL comes complete with the @{"Installer" link INSTALLER} program from Commodore.
  Therefore making installation very simple. Just double-click
  on the @{b}Install@{ub} icon and the installation procedure will start.


  @{b}Manual method@{ub}
  -------------
  The installation should be done in SYS:, not MOSSYS:

  1.
  makedir                   LIBS:DIL
  makedir                   ENVARC:DIL

  2.
  copy User/C/#?            C:
  copy User/Devs/dil.device DEVS:
  copy User/Docs/dil.guide  HELP:
  copy User/Libs/DIL/#?     LIBS:DIL

  3.
  copy User/Prefs/env-archive/DIL/#? ENVARC:DIL


  @{" Requirements " link REQUIREMENTS}

@endnode

@node USAGE "DIL À Usage"

Usage
=====

  @{b}Setup the configuration@{ub}
  -----------------------
  After installation, the first step should be to configure this thing.
  This is done in two steps:

  1. Load the file "ENVARC:DIL/PLUGINDATAPATH" into an editor and set it
  to a path where the plugin can put configs or temporary stuff.
  This path should not point to ram: !

  2. Now load the file "ENVARC:DIL/unit0.cfg" and adjust the values to your
  needs. See @{" Configuration " link CONFIGURATION} for details.

  Ciphers and passphrase
  ----------------------
  If the used plugin is a cipher, it would make sense to have a seed the
  plugin could work with. DIL has builtin functions for that.
  The seed-length depends on the blocksize. It is exactly the blocksize
  in bytes. So, if the blocksize is 512, the seed-length is 512*8 bits = 4906
  bits. If it's 8192, the seed-length will be 8192*8 bits = 65536 bits.
  Blocksizes can be from 512-32768.

  The seed is generated by a passphrase-request or a external passphrase-file.

  At the first start, the passphrase will be verified and a crc-checksum of
  the seed will be stored to "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.crc".
  This checksum is used to verify the entered passphrases in the future.

  For more details on that, please see the Developer Documentation...

  @{b}Making the DosDriver@{ub}
  --------------------
  Now it's time to make a DosDriver for mounting the volume. This can be done
  in the traditional way by or by using the included commands. See @{" Commands " link COMMANDS}
  for details.

  @{b}Finaly@{ub}
  ------
  After mounting, format the volume and you should be ready to go...


  @{" Configuration " link CONFIGURATION}
  @{" Commands      " link COMMANDS}

@endnode

@node CONFIGURATION "DIL À Configuration"

Configuration
=============

  The configuration files for DIL are stored in "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg",
  where <n> is the unit number. There can be any number of units.
  They are plain text-files, which can be edited easily.

  @{b}Editing and syntax@{ub}
  ------------------
  DIL uses its own syntax in configuration-files:

  - Decimal values printed normal
    - as dec     : 012...789
    - as hex-dec : 0x12345678

  - Strings must be within
    - double quotes : "ide.device"
    - single quotes : 'ide.device'

  - Boolean values can be decimals or strings
    - 1 / 0
    - "True" / "False"
    - "Yes" / "No"

  - Comments start with /* and end with */ like in C


  @{b}Configuration sections@{ub}
  ----------------------
  The configuration consists of different sections, which describe the plugin
  to use, the passphrase stuff or the target devcie...

  Sections
  --------
  1. Demo
  2. Plugin
  3. Passphrase
  4. Target device
  5. DosName
  6. DosEnvec
  7. Log

  1. Demo section
  ---------------
  Keyword    : @{b}Demo@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Mandatory
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: If 1, the configuration can't be loaded.
   - This is for security reasons and for the purpose of demonstration.

  2. Plugin section
  -----------------
  Keyword    : @{b}Plugin@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Mandatory
  Defaults   : ""
  Description: Full path and name of the plugin to use

  3. Passphrase section
  ---------------------
  Keyword    : @{b}PassphraseMode@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Mandatory/Optional
  Defaults   : "Keyboard"
  Description: Define the passphrase-input mode.
   - Can be either "Keyboard" or "File".
   - If the plugin is a cipher, so it would need a passphrase-request, this keyword is
     mandatory, else it's optional.
   - If "Keyboard" is used, DIL opens a window asking the user to enter the passphrase.
   - If "File" is used, the passphrase-file (see below) is used instead.

  Keyword    : @{b}PassphraseFile@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Mandatory/Optional
  Defaults   : ""
  Description: Full path and filename of the passphrase-file to use.
   - If PassphraseMode="File" is used, this keyword is mandatory, else it's optional.
   - The file must be between >=6 and <=512 bytes long.
   - NOTE: Imagine passphrase-file on usb-stick? :)

  4. Target device section
  ------------------------
  Keyword    : @{b}Device@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Mandatory
  Defaults   : ""
  Description: The name of the target device.

  Keyword    : @{b}Unit@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Decimal
  Arg type   : Mandatory
  Defaults   : -1
  Description: The unit-number at the target device.

  Keyword    : @{b}Flags@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Decimal
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 0
  Description: The target device unit-flags.

  Keyword    : @{b}InputStd@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : "AUTO"
  Description: Restrict the input standard to a specific type.
   - "AUTO" automaticaly selects the right type.
   - "SCSI" only allows DirectSCSI commands from the source application.
   - "TD64" only allows Trackdisk64 commands.
   - "NSTY" only allows NewStyle commands.
   - "EXEC" only allows exec commands.

  Keyword    : @{b}OutputStd@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : "SAME"
  Description: Convert to a specific standard.
   - "SAME" uses the same standard for output as found on input.
   - "SCSI" converts to a DirectSCSI command.
   - "TD64" converts to a Trackdisk64 command.
   - "NSTY" converts to a NewStyle command.
   - "EXEC" converts to a exec command.

   @{b}Note:@{ub} exec-commands can only be successful if io_Offset+io_Length is < 2^32.
         If a request require to access above the 4gb limit, TD64 is used.

  5. DosName section
  ------------------
  Keyword    : @{b}DosName@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : "DIL<n>" (<n> is unit number)
  Description: This keyword is used by some of the cli-commands "dil#?".
   - It's the name of the volume with that the unit get mounted.
   - If the Keyword is missing, "DIL<n>" will used instead.
   - The name must written without ':'

  6. DosEnvec section
  -------------------
  The following keywords are the same as in standard-mountlists, some
  are mandatory and some are optional.

  Keywords   : @{b}BlockSize | SectorSize@{ub} (512-32768)
               @{b}Surfaces
               BlocksPerTrack | SectorsPerTrack
               SectorsPerBlock
               Reserved
               PreAlloc
               Interleave
               LowCyl
               HighCyl
               Buffers
               BufMemType
               MaxTransfer
               Mask
               BootPri
               DosType
               Baud
               Control

               FileSystem | Handler | EHandler
               StackSize
               Priority
               GlobVec
               Startup
               Activate | Mount
               Forceload@{ub}

  You can use Guido Mersmann's "GiggleDisk" to generate a mountlist for existing
  partitions. Then simple copy&paste this into the configuration-file.

  @{b}Note:@{ub} Don't forget the quotes here, ie: Filesystem = "L:FastFileSystem"

  7. Log section
  --------------
  Keyword    : @{b}LogErrors@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: Whether errors should be logged.

  Keyword    : @{b}LogWarnings@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: Whether warnings should be logged.

  Keyword    : @{b}LogDefault@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: Whether default messages should be logged.

  Keyword    : @{b}LogDebug@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: Whether some debug-output should be logged.

  Keyword    : @{b}LogRAM@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 1
  Description: Whether log to ramdebug (kprintf).

  Keyword    : @{b}LogDisk@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 0
  Description: Whether logging to disk.
    - If this is 1, you also must specify "LogPath" below.
    - The filenames are "unit<unit number>.log".

  Keyword    : @{b}LogPath@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Mandatory if LogDisk=1
  Defaults   : ""
  Description: The path where to put logfiles.

  Keyword    : @{b}LogMultipleFiles@{ub}
  Arg syntax : Boolean
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : 0
  Description: Log to multiple files.
    - If disklog is enabled, this option is used to log to multiple files.
    - The filenames are "unit<unit number>_<datetime>.log".

  Keyword    : @{b}LogFormat@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : "u|d|p|t| m"
  Description: The format of the log-string.
    - u : Current unit number in 1 or 2 digits, ie. "0"
    - d : Date and time, defined by DateFormat below ie. "12:30:00"
    - p : Process name, ie. "dil.device" or "shell"
    - t : Log type, ie. "Warning", "Debug"
    - m : The log message itself.

  @{b}Note:@{ub} The control chars are case-sensitive!

  Keyword    : @{b}DateFormat@{ub}
  Arg syntax : String
  Arg type   : Optional
  Defaults   : "H:M:S"
  Description: The format of the date-string.
    - Y : Year in 4 digits, ie. "2009"
    - y : Year in 2 digits, ie. "07"
    - N : Month in words , ie. "Jan"
    - m : Month in 2 digits, ie. "01"
    - d : Day in 2 digits, ie. "01"
    - H : Hour in 2 digits, ie. "12"
    - M : Minute in 2 digits, ie. "30"
    - S : Secound in 2 digits, ie. "00"

  @{b}Note:@{ub} The control chars are case-sensitive!


  @{" Usage    " link USAGE}
  @{" Commands " link COMMANDS}

@endnode

@node COMMANDS "DIL À Commands"

Commands
========

  There are some commands avail, which are helpfull for basic stuff:

  @{" dilCheckCfg     " link DILCHECKCFG} Check the configuration for a unit

  @{" dilPlugInfo     " link DILPLUGINFO} Show informations about a plugin

  @{" dilGenDosDriver " link DILGENDOSDRIVER} Generate a DosDriver for a unit

  @{" dilMount        " link DILMOUNT} Mount a unit
  @{" dilUnMount      " link DILUNMOUNT} Unmount a unit

  @{" dilRevoke       " link DILREVOKE} Revoke a unit


  @{" Usage         " link USAGE}
  @{" Configuration " link CONFIGURATION}

@endnode

@node DILCHECKCFG "DIL À Command À dilCheckCfg"

dilCheckCfg
===========

  Format
    [UNIT <number>]

  Template
    UNIT=U/A/N

  Purpose
    Check the configuration

  Path
    C:dilCheckCfg

  Specification
    Check the configuration-file "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg".
    Usefull to test configs prior mounting.

    @{b}UNIT=U/A/N@{ub} The dil.device unit-number.

  Example
    dilCheckCfg 0

@endnode

@node DILPLUGINFO "DIL À Command À dilPlugInfo"

dilPlugInfo
===========

  Format
    [NAME <file>]

  Template
    NAME=N/A

  Purpose
    Show informations about a plugin

  Path
    C:dilPlugInfo

  Specification
    Shows some informations about a plugin.

    @{b}NAME=N/A@{ub} The filename of the plugin.
      You can write the filename as "LIBS:DIL/foobar.dilp", "foobar.dilp"
      or "foobar".

  Example
    dilPlugInfo foobar

@endnode

@node DILGENDOSDRIVER "DIL À Command À dilGenDosDriver"

dilGenDosDriver
===============

  Format
    [UNIT/A/N <number>] [TO <path>]

  Template
    UNIT=U/A/N,TO=T/K

  Purpose
    Generate a DosDriver for a unit

  Path
    C:dilGenDosDriver

  Specification
    Generate a DosDriver from "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg".
    A DosDriver is needed if you want to mount via the system instead of
    "dilMount".

    @{b}UNIT=U/A/N@{ub} The dil.device unit-number.

    @{b}TO=T/K@{ub} The optional target path or file.
      - If "DosName" is not configured in "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg",
        a file called "DIL<n>" is generated in the given <path>.
      - If this argument is not given, the output is done in the shell.

  Examples
    1. Just show me the DosDriver for "ENVARC:DIL/unit0.cfg":
    dilGenDosDriver 0

    2. Save the DosDriver for "ENVARC:DIL/unit0.cfg":
    dilGenDosDriver 0 TO DEVS:DosDrivers

@endnode

@node DILMOUNT "DIL À Command À dilMount"

dilMount
========

  Format
    [UNIT <number>]

  Template
    UNIT=U/A/N

  Purpose
    Mount a unit

  Path
    C:dilMount

  Specification
    Try to mount the device configured in "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg".

    @{b}UNIT=U/A/N@{ub} The dil.device unit-number.

  Example
    dilMount 0

@endnode

@node DILUNMOUNT "DIL À Command À dilUnMount"

dilUnMount
==========

  Format
    [UNIT <number>]

  Template
    UNIT=U/A/N

  Purpose
    Unmount a unit

  Path
    C:dilUnMount

  Specification
    Try to unmount the device configured in "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg".

    @{b}UNIT=U/A/N@{ub} The dil.device unit-number.

  Example
    dilUnMount 0

@endnode

@node DILREVOKE "DIL À Command À dilRevoke"

dilRevoke
=========

  Format
    [UNIT <number>] [QUIET]

  Template
    UNIT=U/A/N,QUIET=Q/S

  Purpose
    Revoke a unit

  Path
    C:dilRevoke

  Specification
    Revoke the device configured in "ENVARC:DIL/unit<n>.cfg".
    This command kicks out the passphrase from the memory. At the next
    read/write-request, the user must enter the passphrase again or
    the passphrase-file will be re-validated.

    @{b}UNIT=U/A/N@{ub} The dil.device unit-number.

    @{b}QUIET=Q/S@{ub} If specified, no output will be done.

  Example
    dilRevoke 0 Q

@endnode

